<head><title>The Goat Ate My Computer!</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFD0">
<center><h1>The Goat Ate My Computer!</h1><br><strong>By Mary Pride</strong></center>
<p><hr>
"All the homeschoolers I know keep goats -- and I don't like goats!" The speaker was a frustrated father. He wanted to homeschool his children, but he didn't want to become a Future Farmer of America.
<p>
"All the homeschoolers I know have two computers -- and I don't like computers!" The speaker was a frustrated mother. She wanted to homeschool her children, but was afraid she lacked the high-tech skills to do the job.
<p>
"All the homeschoolers I know have two heads and sixteen arms. I'd better grow some more heads and arms." Now we're talking! Who couldn't use a few more heads or arms? Forget the goats and computers -- slap me some organic upgrades and I'll awe everybody at the next support group meeting!
<p>
Awed questioner: "How do you handle all eight of your children, Mrs. Octopus?"
<p>
Me: "Oh, my, it's easy. I just wrap a friendly arm around each of their shoulders and keep them sitting quietly by me while they do their studies. It's no trouble at all."
<p>
You say that, thanks to the magic of DNA, you can't grow extra arms and heads? Then we're back to the goats and computers. Which of these is your passport to join the inner circle of Homeschool Hotshots? Vote here:
<p><ol>
<li>You need the goats.
<li>You need at least one computer.
<li>And it better have a CD-ROM drive.
<li>Or you'll have to supplement with chickens.
<li>None of the above.
</ol><p>
As the owner of umpteen computers and zero goats, it is of course my duty to cast my vote for option C above. Yet I must confess that, although I actually co-authored a book on educational software, I teach all my children to read with old-fashioned phonics lessons. Oops! Guess I'm not a hotshot after all. It gets worse; since we live in Fabulous Fenton, a suburban community bordered (and sometimes covered) by what my children lovingly call the "Merrymuck" river, the zoning authorities will not allow us to keep goats, chickens, or even harmless little wooly lambs. Also, because of my magazine duties, I no longer have the time to bake homemade bread, make yogurt from scratch, sew my own clothes, or plant herbaceous borders. Instead, our bread is by Bill (who with more strength gets the job done quicker), our yogurt is by Dannon, our clothes are by Wal-Mart, and our flowers are by accident.
<p>
So how do I have the audacity not only to read this magazine, but to publish it? Easy! Homeschooling isn't about sewing, or gardening, or Internet surfing. It can, and often does, include all of these, but you don't need any of them. 
<p>
Once you get past reading, riting, rithmetic, and reasoning -- what our Principle Approach pals call "the four R's" and our Classical Education buddies call "the tools of learning"-almost anything goes. You will find your children can learn anything they need to know no matter where you live and no matter what learning tools are available to you. That's why there's no real contradiction between Joan Donaldson's article in this issue about her technology-free country homeschool and Jason Rippetoe's article about using the Internet in your homeschool. Both options are valid. Both are exciting. Both work.
<p>
Sure, math drill by computer is more fun and less strain -- but flashcards work, too. True, milking the goats helps children learn responsibility -- but so does caring for a baby sister. Those who live in the midst of awesome natural beauty can give their children many advantages -- but so can those who live jammed into an inner-city apartment. 
<p>
Your child's best teacher is neither a computer nor a goat, but you. Just keep improving your own knowledge and wisdom. Keep searching for the best educational resources that fit your own life and your goals for your children. Keep protecting your children from evil and surrounding them with everything you can find that is good. Then, whether you wear a kerchief, or a hard hat, or a little propeller beanie, you will be a Homeschool Hotshot. For real. 
<p>
<hr>
<strong>COPYRIGHT INFORMATION</strong>
<br>Copyright 1994 Home Life Inc. 
<br>Originally published in Practical Homeschooling No. 5.
<br>All rights reserved. This article or any part of it may not be published on any Internet or WWW site, or any BBS, or any other electronic or print medium, or any other medium, without our expression written permission. To request permission, please fax 314-225-0743 and describe the article, where you would like to publish it, and how many people you expect to read your publication. We will get back to you with our response as soon as possible.
</body>

