<head><title>CDROM: What It Is, Does</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFD0">
<center><h1>CDROM: What It Is, What It Does</h1><br><strong>By Mary Pride</strong></center>
<p><hr>
As you may have guessed by now, PRACTICAL HOMESCHOOLING takes computer education seriously! We believe that, while traditional styles of education are both valid and effective, computer education can add a lot to the party.
<p>
Right now let's take a look at a brand-new technology -- CD-ROM -- and what it can do for you!
<hr><p>
<strong>What Is CD-ROM?</strong>
<p>
CD-ROM, which stands for "Compact Disc -- Read-Only Memory" is not really new, since it's been kicked around for almost a decade now. What is new is that this technology has finally become fast and affordable enough to tempt the wary consumer.
<p>
A CD-ROM looks exactly like its cousin, the compact disc you play in your stereo system. Instead of just audio sound, though, a CD-ROM can also hold data (hundreds of books fit on one disc), graphics (hundreds of beautiful full-color pictures), and animation (mini movie and cartoon sequences, in sizes from postage-stamp to full-screen). More: it can hold all of them at once! And since it's a computer technology, you can interact with all that sound, sight, and action.
<p>
The CD-ROM is not only a hundredfold bigger in storage capacity than a floppy disc; it is also quite cheap to manufacture, once the information has been produced and copied onto a "master" disc. At the present time, it also is impossible for software pirates to copy a CD-ROM, except by the arduous and expensive process of filling up dozens of floppies or clogging up entire hard drives. All this means that both software publishers and consumers have many reasons for interest in CD-ROM.
<p>
The first commercial CD-ROM products cost an arm and a leg, thanks to the expense of creating the products and the tiny initial market. Those of us watching the industry predicted that CD-ROM would come on with a bang, though, when the price of the drives dropped low enough to create a sizable market. This would enable software publishers to drop their prices in return -- which is exactly what has happened. With the exception of a few vastly overpriced CD-ROM encyclopedias, which you can often get free anyway as part of the bundle that comes with your drive (the strategy here is to price a product high, then the customer thinks he's getting a GREAT deal when he gets "$1,200 worth of free CD-ROM software!" with his CD-ROM drive), prices for CD-ROMs are right in the same range as prices for floppy-based products.
<p>
<strong>What Kind of CD-ROM Drive Should I Get?</strong>
<p>
We're not going to bore you with a lot of techno-talk. What you want is a double-speed, multisession-capable, XA-compatible CD-ROM drive. You want double speed, because drives without it trudge along too slowly to make the most of the new generation of CD-ROM software. You want multisession capability just in case you end up using Kodak's new PhotoCDs. These allow you to have the pictures you take with your regular old camera stored on a CD disc; multisession capability means you can take the same disc back later to have more photos stored on it. This saves you money. You want XA compatibility because, like multisession capability, it proves the manufacturer is up with the times. The XA format allows audio -- lots more of it -- and data to be stored on the same track. It also allows the computer to receive data from the disc at the same time the disc is playing audio. The buzz is that publishers will be producing lots of good stuff in XA format -- watch for it!
<p>
<strong>Should I Wait for Something Better?</strong>
<p>
We have friends who are convinced you should wait until the new quadra-speed CD-ROM drives come out, sometime in 1994. Also on the horizon are CD-ROMs that can hold 74 minutes of full-screen movie video, using a new standard called "Video CD." Let's take these one by one. 
<p>
First, sure it would be nicer to have a faster drive -- but when exactly will these be coming out? Computer-land is notorious for "vaporware" -- products announced years before they actually hit the marketplace. And those of us with some experience know we won't be the first on our block to buy any gee-whiz new hardware; not until the inevitable bugs have time to get worked out.
<p>
Against the possibly faster speed of future (more expensive) drives you also have to trade off the fun and learning that you'll miss out on by waiting for one. Paradoxically, the only thing you are likely to gain by waiting patiently is a product whose only selling point is that you won't have to be so patient while using it!
<p>
Now for problem #2 -- video CD. Existing CD-ROM drives will be able to use it. You'll just need to add another hardware board to your computer. This board will decode the specially compressed data on the CD. Again, no real reason to wait.
<p>
<strong>What Can CD-ROM Do For Me?</strong>
<p>
Imagine a book with animated illustrations that you can stop or start at will. Imagine a book that you can ask questions, such as "Tell me what this word means" or "Show me all the other places this word is used in this book." Imagine a book that can talk to you . . . in several different languages!
<p>
<strong>Books that Talk, Sing, and Dance.</strong> In the portable realm, the day of computer visionary Alan Kay's "Dynabook" is already here. Voyager Company already is selling a line of "Electronic Books" that let you electronically "dog-ear" a page, underline a passage, look up a word in a glossary, or find the other places that word occurs in the book. Designed for use on the Macintosh PowerBook laptop, these come on disk and thus only contain scanty animation and sound capabilities.
<p>
Take the same idea and put it on CD-ROM. Suddenly you have room for hours of excellent sound and speech, hundreds of color animations, and entire encyclopedias full of text. Which is why encyclopedias and other large reference works were among the first CD-ROM products. 
<p>
Much more fun for most of us, and among the most acclaimed CD-ROM products, are Brderbund's "Living Books." At present these include two titles we have seen (Just Grandmother and Me and Arthur's Teacher Trouble) and two we haven't (The Tortoise and the Hare and The New Kid on the Block). These books are promoted as "educational," but don't kid yourself; they have almost zip educational value. Fun? That they are. Our kids have played with both of them for hours, not to mention with the real paperback books that also come tucked in the packages. Basically, you click on items on each "page" to see and hear them do goofy things. Practically every object on every page is clickable. Educational value is supposed to come from children "reading along" with the narrated text. This, however, is read phrase-by-phrase, instead of word-by-word, and at such a rate of speed that beginning readers couldn't possibly keep up even in English, let alone in Spanish or Japanese (two other options).
<p>
For educational read-along value you need to turn to the "Kids Can READ!" series from Discis Knowledge Research. Some of the titles in this series, such as the infamous Scary Poems for Rotten Kids, are not at all suitable for home use, whatever jaded media types and politically correct educrats may say. However, the CD-ROMs from Discis based on wholesome books, such as Beatrix Potter's Peter Rabbit, allow children to read along page by page, word by word, or phrase by phrase. Children can see and hear the meanings of unknown words as well. (For a more detailed review, see Prides' Guide.)
<p>
<strong>Encyclopedias that Talk, Sing, and Dance.</strong> Programmers keep thinking of new ways to make information more interesting and memorable, using CD-ROM. All multimedia encyclopedias now feature birdcalls and other animal sounds, for example. Video clips of famous historical events, such as the moon rocket launch, also appear on CD-ROM encyclopedias. The 1993 edition of Grolier's Multimedia Encyclopedia ($399) from Software Toolworks, with versions for Macintosh, DOS, and MPC, even has "moving maps." These let you see how political boundaries changed over time. The boundaries shrink and grow before your very eyes. Neat!
<p>
<strong>Music Appreciation.</strong> This is another area where CD-ROM shines. Imagine hearing a musical extract, right along with an analysis of the score by a top-notch music critic. Imagine viewing and visual biography of a composer. Imagine clicking on an illustration of an instrument to hear it play. Imagine playing games that teach you how to play an instrument or introduce you to music theory. It's all here!
<p>
So far most music CD-ROMs have been built around a famous piece of music, such as Mozart's Magic Flute or Brahms' German Requiem, both from Warner New Media. You'll find quite a few of these written up in Prides' Guide to Educational Software. New on the market, and definitely of more use to most homeschoolers, is The Musical World of Professor Piccolo from Opcode Interactive. This gamelike Windows program for 16 MHz 386-based PCs and above teaches children an incredible amount of music theory and music appreciation. Styles covered are classical, jazz, rock, and church music. You enter "buildings" representing these musical styles through a main screen. Once inside, you can choose from dozens of activities. Play musical games in the "Arcade." Click on symphony orchestra players to hear them play. See and hear an interactive analysis of Hayden's Symphony No. 88. Go to the Library and flip through the onscreen card catalog to research music terms and instruments. Hear the band play in the Rock Club or the Jazz Club. Take a full-blown interactive music theory course at the Music School, or fiddle around with a game of Musical Pursuit. As you can see, this one program combines all the best features from dozens of diskette-based programs, as well as being the only music-appreciation product we know of that gives church music proper credit for its foundational role in the development of Western music.
<p>
<strong>Foreign Languages.</strong> CD-ROM is revolutionizing foreign-language learning. See our Special Report on 10 top foreign-language software products -- eight of which come on CD-ROM -- elsewhere in this issue.
<p>
<strong>History.</strong> That old MECC classic, The Oregon Trail, is the first and best example of a history simulation. Fancied up from its original diskette version, the CD-ROM edition features a rich soundtrack (including period songs), colorful graphics, and talking characters you meet along the Trail. Your goal: to bring your companions and yourself safely from Independence, Missouri to Oregon. Based on the genuine experiences of the early pioneers -- minus encounters with warlike Indians, which are no longer politically correct to mention -- this engaging adventure can be played over and over. You have to spend your money and time wisely, take good advice, and be a good shot to make it successfully to the end of the Trail.
<p>
<strong>Preschool Discovery.</strong> For this, CD-ROM is a natural. Little ones can click around on the screen to make all sorts of interesting and educational things happen. You don't need a CD-ROM for this, as Brderbund's Playroom and Treehouse products prove. But CD-ROM allows the programmers to add many more games and rooms to a single program. It also allows them to let different things happen each time a child clicks on an object.
<p>
An example of the new dimensions CD-ROM brings to discovery software is Allie's Playhouse from Opcode Interactive. By the same people who brought you Professor Piccolo, this Windows-based CD-ROM product includes 16 different educational activities for children ages 3-8. Following the approach popularized by Brderbund's "Playhouse" series, you enter the activities through clicking on objects in an onscreen room. For example, you click on the clock to enter the clock activities.
<p>
Like many other interdisciplinary programs for this age group, Allie's Playhouse includes simple counting and phonics games and an onscreen coloring book. Unique activities include: a body part recognition game, constructing and playing your own goofy musical instrument, time-telling with Mr. Clock and "Digi," identifying animals by sight and sound, continent identification, 18 sing-along nursery rhymes, and planet identification. Children can also play and record their own music, using a variety of onscreen instruments. A "Child Safety" mode allows you to keep kids out of the rest of your hard disk.
<p>
<strong>Just Plain Fun.</strong> Our lives should have room for a little gaiety, don't you think? If you agree, you and your children will love three new titles from Humongous Entertainment. All feature lush color graphics reminiscent of Sierra Online's hand-painted backgrounds, but slightly more surrealistic. Cabinets and doors bulge at impossible angles. This adds a pinch of liveliness to the cartoon illustrations, which you can click on here and there to make wacky things happen.
<p>
In two of these wholesome titles, the main character has to search for objects and solve some simple puzzles in order to win his objective. In Fatty Bear's Birthday Surprise, Fatty Bear must locate the garage opener, catch the escaped puppy, make a cake, and find the missing letters from Kayla's birthday sign. When you finish roaming about the house and yard doing all this, Kayla gets her party. Along the way you can play a bowling game or play tunes on the piano. In Putt-Putt Joins the Parade the character is a charming little car with the voice of a child. Putt-Putt needs to find a puppy, rescue a lost little car, gas up, and mow some lawns, among other things, before he can join the parade. Putt-Putt's Fun Pack stars the same character, but has no storyline. Instead you get six on-screen games, from Checkers (Putt-Putt models good winning and good losing) to sliding puzzles and Concentration. Games have varying levels of difficulty. Not yet seen: Fatty Bear's Fun Pack and Putt-Putt Goes to the Moon. These titles are due out in November (PC version) and January (Macintosh).
<p>
All the Humongous programs are cute and cheerful, without being the least bit cloying. Even the credits at the end have balloons you can click on to pop as they float by! Try doing that with a paper-and-pencil workbook!
<p>
<strong>Where to Find It</strong>
<p><ul>
<li>Brderbund Software, 500 Redwood Blvd. PO Box 6121, Novato, CA 94948-6121. (415) 382-4400. Fax: (415) 382-4582. Each "Living Book," $39.95. Macintosh and MPC.
<p>
<li>Discis Knowledge Research, PO Box 66, Buffalo, NY 14223-0066. 1-800-567-4321. Each title, $29.95. All 11 titles in the "Kids Can READ!" series are multiformat, meaning you can use the same disc with DOS, Windows, and Macintosh.
<p>
<li>Humongous Entertainment, 13110 NE 177th Pl, Box 180, Woodinville, WA 98072. (206) 485-1212. Fatty Bear, Putt-Putt Parade, $54.95 each. Putt-Putt Fun Pack, $29.95. Free demo disk while supplies last. Specify IBM-PC or color Mac.
<p>
<li>MECC, 6160 Summit Drive North, Minneapolis, MN 55430-4003. 1-800-685-MECC.  The Oregon Train CD-ROM, $79, Macintosh or MPC. Diskette versions available for Mac, DOS, and Windows.
<p>
<li>Opcode Interactive, 3950 Fabian Way, Suite 100, Palo Alto, CA 94303-9643. (415) 494-1112. Fax: (415) 494-1113. Professor Piccolo, $69.95, MPC. Allie's Playhouse, $59.95, MPC.
<p>
<li>Software Toolworks, 60 Leveroni Court, Novato, CA 94949-9913. Orders: 800-234-3088. Inquiries: (415) 883-3000. Fax: (415) 883-3303.
<p>
<li>Voyager Company, 1351 Pacific Coast Highway, Santa Monica, CA 90401. 1-800-446-2001. Fax: (310) 394-2156.
<p>
<li>Warner New Media, 3500 W. Olive Ave., Suite 1050, Burbank, CA 91505. (818) 955-9999. Fax: (818) 955-6499.
</ul><p>
<strong>For More Info on CD-ROM</strong>
<p><ul>
<li>For those with a CD-ROM drive, an IBM-compatible computer, and a lot of curiosity, the CD -- ROM Directory disc covers what's happening in the industry from a professional point of view. Order online from CompuServe by going CDVEN and then following the command sequence Library - Browse - Compton's.
<p>
<li>CD-ROM Today is a bright new magazine with all the latest on this industry, from a consumer's point of view. Secular perspective: you may want to cruise the issues before your children see them and rip out any questionable ads. One year (6 issues) $20.95. CD-ROM Today, 23-00 Route 208, Fair Lawn, NJ 07410. (201) 703-9505. Fax: (201) 703-9509.
<p>
<li>NautilusCD is the premier CD-ROM magazine -- on CD-ROM! Every issue is packed with demos, games, interviews, features, clip art, music clips, multimedia "how tos," and much more. Sprightly, colorful interface. Our children love this "virtual magazine." Not really pricey for high-tech-savvy families when you consider every issue includes hundreds of usable software files. Macintosh and IBM-compatible editions available. $137.40 for 12 issues ($11.45 per issue). NautilusCD, The Multimedia Magazine, 7001 Discovery Blvd, Dublin, OH 43017. 1-800-637-3742. Fax: (614) 761-4110. Sample issues are available at varying prices from discount software catalogs.
</ul><p>
<strong>Baseline systems for running CD-ROM</strong>
<p><ul>
<li>Macintosh: Color Mac (LC and up), 1 MB RAM, hard drive with decent amount of space available, System 6.0.7 or later/System 7 or later, 12" or bigger color monitor. With a 14" or larger monitor, even your LC will be able to run Mac II programs!
<p>
<li>MS-DOS: IBM-compatible, 12 MHz 386SX or better, 2 MB RAM, DOS 5.0 or later, hard drive with decent amount of space available, VGA or SVGA monitor, mouse.
<p>
<li>Windows:  IBM-compatible, 12 MHz 386SX or better, 4 MB RAM, Windows 3.1, Microsoft CD-ROM extensions, hard drive with decent amount of space available, VGA or SVGA monitor, mouse.
<p>
<li>MPC: IBM-compatible, 12 MHz 80386SX or later, 4 MB RAM, DOS 3.1 or later, Windows 3.1 with Microsoft CD-ROM Extensions 2.2 or later, 30 MB hard drive, MPC-compatible CD-ROM drive and sound board, VGA or SVGA monitor, mouse.
<p>
<li>All CD-ROM programs require a CD-ROM drive. Your IBM-compatible will run CD-ROM much better with a sound card (we recommend ProAudio Spectrum 16). Macintosh systems do not require a sound card, but will sound better with one. Computer-friendly speakers are quite inexpensive these days -- as low as $29 for a set of two -- and again add a lot to the CD-ROM experience.
</ul><p>
<strong>Getting Started with CD-ROM</strong>
<p>
The Educorp CD-ROM Sampler, which we got on special for $8.95, is a great way for Macintosh owners to check out the possibilities of a new CD-ROM drive. An elegant interface presents five categories: desktop publishing, education, entertainment, general interest, and multimedia. Click on a category and it brings up a window of program titles, each with an accompanying screen shot from the program. Click on the screen shot and you will either find more information about that program or -- and this is what you really want -- a program demo! (Demos require color Mac with minimum 4 MB memory and 13" color monitor.)
<p>
The Sampler is frequently updated. These are the programs we found on it at press time. We saw quite a few interactive books represented, none of which had demos. These were mostly classic titles, such as 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea and Beauty and the Beast. Reference works included nature titles such as Grolier Encyclopedia, a multimedia encyclopedia of Butterflies, the Dictionary of the Living World, and Small Blue Planet (nice demo of the latter). Five music titles were included, all with complete demos, from So You Want to be a Rock and Roll Star to The Orchestra. Some preschool titles and a nice demo of Learn French with Asterix were also in the Education section. Entertainment demos included Journeyman Project, Hell Cab, Iron Helix, Beyond the Wall of Stars, Better Dead, Battle Chess, and Lunicus, to name a few of the 18 programs featured. Under the heading General Interest were some titles we might consider more educational: How Computers Work and The New Family Bible, to name two. Others in this category were mainly shareware collections and current-events titles such as Desert Storm. The Desktop Publishing and Multimedia categories will also show you some of the stuff you can do with your upgraded Mac, from jazzy background sound clips for your presentations to royalty-free photos you can plug into your publications and presentations. One gripe: we wish the program titles were coded to show if you were going to get a demo or just a screen of information. 
<p>
<strong>Where to Get It:</strong> Educorp, 7434 Trade St., San Diego, CA 92121-2410. Warning: the Educorp catalog includes some "swimsuit" and "nude" art disks. The latest edition of the catalog does not include any explicit pictures, but still be aware that this company sells a few disks and CD-ROMs with this type of material.
<p>
<hr>
