<head><title>The Case for CD-I</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFD0">
<center><h1>TV-Top Education: The Case for CD-I</h1><br><strong>By Mary Pride</strong></center>
<p><hr>
"I don't understand computers and I never will. But I sure wish my family could enjoy some of the new educational software." You're just in time for what may be a major trend of the 90s -- TV-top consoles that play multimedia CDs.
<p>
This new generation of players do not require a computer. Instead, you plug them into your TV monitor or TV-free video monitor. No installation procedures, no bulky manuals, no anguished calls to tech support, no typing on keyboards, no need to struggle with AUTOEXEC.BAT files or System 7. All you have to know is how to pop a CD into a player, watch TV, and use a remote control
<p>
For this ease of use, you pay a price. You can't save your progress. Every time you play a program you start at the beginning. You also can't print out your work results. You can't easily type in answers, thus losing one main form of easy interaction. (Some programs do allow you to enter one letter at a time by clicking on an onscreen keyboard. Agonizing!) In exchange, you get to use a bigger screen, if your TV or TV-free system has one. You don't have to set up a separate computer room, either. Wherever you watch TV is where you will be playing with your educational software. 
<p>
<strong>At the moment at least seven devices are fighting it out for the TV-top console market: </strong>
<p><ul>
<li>Philips Electronics' CD-i (it stands for CD-ROM Interactive).
<p>
<li>Commodore's Amiga-based CD32, a deserving product with what many people consider the weakest top management team in the industry behind it.
<p>
<li>The much-hyped 3DO Multiplayer, which will be produced by a variety of manufacturers, of whom Panasonic is the first.
<p>
<li>Pioneer's LaserActive, a pricey quad-speed device with a huge 12" platter. Pay an extra $350 for the Laser Karaoke package and you can sing along.
<p>
<li>The Jaguar, from the amazing shrinking company Atari, once a games giant but now a mere shadow of its former self.
<p>
<li>New 32-bit machines from Sega and Nintendo-more of the same from the companies that have turned active American boys into armchair warriors, only with better and faster pictures.
</ul><p>
It's anyone's guess as to which of these devices will nail down the huge games market. Only one of these companies, however, has made a serious effort to attract educational software developers. And the winner, whose product we will discuss for the remainder of this article, is . . . CD-i!
<p>
Dutch giant Philips Electronics, who invented CD-i, are the same folks who brought you the audio CD and the VCR. Their CD-i player was at first dismissed as too expensive (true at the time) with a relatively low-end processor (a 15 MHz 68070, about the same as a 8 MHz 68000, as seen only in ancient 286s and used Mac Pluses). Reviewers also snickered at the CD-i's remote (a hard-to-twiddle tiny joystick) and bemoaned the lack of high-quality software available for it.
<p>
Philips has met all these challenges head-on. First, they dramatically lowered the price and upped the device's abilities. You're probably not too excited to hear that a CD-i machine can play audio CDs and Kodak's new PhotoCDs, unless you don't already own a CD player or are dying to see your family photos on your TV. The real breakthrough is that for the first time in human history, you now can add a cartridge that allows you to play CD-sized digital video movies. I kid you not, folks -- they actually can fit an entire feature movie on one of those little golden discs. And the movie looks even better than it does on video! We previewed the "White Christmas" CD-i, and were simply blown away by the picture detail and the lush colors. No annoying video flicker, either, and you can't stretch the tape because there is no tape to stretch.
<p>
The newly designed remote has a much more sophisticated joystick. You can also purchase a touchpad or a special large trackball device for young children, the "Roller Controller." And Philips' publishing groups alone have released over 130 titles for the CD-i system.
<p>
Philips does not write most of their own software, of course. Like other hardware manufacturers, they approach successful software companies and encourage them to write programs for the CD-i platform. One such software company is Optimum Resource, home of the "Stickybear" software series. Optimum Resource not only develops CD-i software, but puts together package deals on educational CD-i software and sells the CD-i machines. We got our review samples, plus the loan of a CD-i console, from Optimum Resource. 
<p>
Few CD-i titles are currently available on CD-ROM and vice versa, due to incompatibilities between the two. One exception is Stickybear Reading ($29.98). We reviewed the computer version of this title in a previous issue. The CD-i version is identical, except that the soundtrack plays continuously and you can't save or print your scores. Designed for young children ages 4-8, this extremely popular title lets kids "bop" pictures into words and back again, match words and pictures, find the missing word to accompany a sentence and picture, and create sentences that come to life, all in both English and Spanish. The Stickybear family, who add personality to this program, are as genial and wholesome as can be.
<p>
Another title you can find on both CD-ROM and CD-i is Compton's Encyclopedia ($299). You can view all 26 printed volumes on your TV. That may not sound too exciting, but look at what the multimedia version offers that the books don't. Hypertext links between articles allow you to instantly jump to a new topic that interests you and then back to the original article and video clips of famous events, such as JFK launching the space race or a time-elapsed photo sequence of the planet Jupiter spinning. Hear and see JFK in full TV quality, not the jerky, blurry postage-stamp animation of many CD-ROM products. A "Time Machine" sends you flying past pictures related to different epochs. Click on the time period that interests you and you get a visual menu of topics related to that period, from which you can access visual and text information. A world atlas lets you click on any part of the globe to find out information about it. You can also reach into the encyclopedia through a regular index, or look up any word in an onscreen dictionary. Compton's has a lot more features than we have room to list here. Our children think it is "pretty fabulous."
<p>
These two titles-Stickybear Reading CD-i and Compton's Encyclopedia CD-i-are free when you purchase a player and an educational library bundle from Optimum Resource, Inc., the producer of the Stickybear series. The player, these two programs, and your choice of the "Early Learning Library" or the "Fine Arts Library" costs $849. The player, both libraries, and the two free titles costs $1099. At press time, the retail value of each library bundle was around $400. If you actually want all the bundled titles, that knocks the price of the player itself down to just over $200. Call Optimum Resource, Inc. to find which titles are currently being offered in these libraries.
<p>
We had the chance to review quite a few titles from both libraries, plus a few not included in either library. Some are really nifty and others are just so-so. Here are our findings.
<p>
Richard Scarry's Busiest Neighborhood and Richard Scarry's Best Neighborhood are the winners in the Early Learning Library. At just $24.98 each, these discs are a great value. In each, you navigate around a neighborhood populated by the winsome and colorful animal characters from author/illustrator Richard Scarry's popular children's books. As you travel through the streets, cars drive by, characters move about, and slapstick mishaps occur. Wacky things also happen when you click on particular characters and objects. Every shop in the neighborhood has two to four objects to click and at least one mildly educational activity. For example, you select items to construct a sundae in the ice-cream shop and learn the names and sounds of a few instruments in the music shop. The discs contain a lot of typical Scarry humor: the balloon seller floats away, Pa Pig chases his hat, the weatherman's pants get blown off by the wind, revealing (you guessed it) loud underwear. Our younger children love these discs.
<p>
A Visit to Sesame Street: Numbers and A Visit to Sesame Street: Letters ($29.98 each) star the world's best-known cartoon characters. You can interact with a number of objects littering the street, or visit Bert and Ernie's house and Big Bird's nest. In Numbers, you can also visit the Count (a Dracula-like character) at his castle; in Letters, it's the Snuffleupagus's cave. Every location has lots of objects you can interact with. Play "Shape-O-Matic" or "What's My Rhyme?" Click on any of the books scattered on the floors of the houses to read them, or play the movies in the onscreen movie players. Our children labeled this one "only slightly educational."
<p>
Tell Me Why I and II ($34.98 each) are an attempt to provide visual and auditory answers to 175 questions each. They each cover the same five areas of interest -- How Things Work, Our World, How Things Began, The Zoo, and The Human Body. Using these is like visiting a museum. You click on a "door," go into a "room," and click on a "picture" on the wall to launch the presentation. The presentations are not all that gripping, mostly consisting of still photographs accompanied by narration. Both discs are adapted from the book series and are secular in outlook.
<p>
Dark Fables of Aesop is just illustrations with accompanying narration of 12 famous fables. The "Dark" part comes from the creepy introduction, where Aesop enters a temple to select a scroll from the "Library of Wisdom." Interactivity is provided by an opening screen with clickable pictures of the animals, each launching its story, and a maze game with three levels and 60 mazes. Not worth the $24.98, in our opinion.
<p>
Sandy's Circus Adventure ($24.98) is like an interactive TV cartoon show. Sandy, a lovable seal, has the opportunity to join the circus. At crucial points in the story you can decide which action Sandy should take. You also can color in Sandy and the other characters to your taste before running the story. Frothy and fun.
<p>
Paint School ($19.98) is an onscreen coloring book with hundreds of scenes to color. Unlike a regular coloring book, it starts with a guided tour of the paint tools. These are standard computer paint tools: a box maker, a circle maker, different sized paintbrushes, and a zoom button that lets you paint tiny details. You can even "paint" an area with one of the provided patterns, for some pretty wild effects, or cut the painting into puzzle pieces and put them together. Ted (who reviewed it before he got sick) says, "This is a pretty fun program. I could have played it all day!"
<p>
Our children gave Children's Musical Theatre ($29.98) a "thumbs down." This contains four original songs that you can customize by changing words, leaving out various instruments, or selecting "classical," "pop," or "country" style. The animated band then plays the song. B-O-R-I-N-G.
<p>
Cartoon Jukebox ($24.98), another musical offering, is more successful. Here you can choose from 10 all-time favorites such as "Old MacDonald Had a Farm," instead of Brand X originals. As in Sandy's Circus Adventure, you can color the cheerful cartoon characters before running the animation of them singing the song. You have 50 cartoon pages to color with your 10-color palette. The so-called "games" included are of the nature of "Click on the character and hear a solo."
<p>
Of the dozens of art discs we reviewed, some compare unfavorably with books while others make a stab at doing something with the technology. Treasures of the Smithsonian ($49.98) was the worst. You'd think that an institution with over one-half billion annual budget and more visitors annually than Disneyland could produce a fancy disc. What a disappointment to find no video clips; sluggish movement from place to place in the program; no way to return to your previous spot once you pursue a subtopic; no rhyme or reason for the choice of artifacts (we understand why they show us the Hope Diamond, but who cares about penguin stickers?); and much, much less. We also could do without the socialist bias and worshipful promotion of paganism. Hear the narrator intone, "No wonder [some tribe] worshipped the jaguar!" and "Perhaps this image helped him predict the future." If Clinton actually wished to cut the budget, he could start right here. 
<p>
In contrast, both Art of the Czars ($39.98) and Amparo Museum present a fascinating mix of history, art, and geography. In both, you navigate visually by clicking on sites, people, and art categories. Art of the Czars presents the Czars and Czarinas who contributed to the Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg, whose artworks are displayed on the disc. Too bad these artworks include some nudes. Amparo Museum tours Mexican art history via several Aztec and Spanish sites and museums. As an extra, the Amparo Museum narration is available at any time in your choice of Spanish, English, French, and German. Other titles available for $39.98 include Renaissance Gallery, Renaissance of Florence (a Cindy Award winner, but panned by our kids), French Impressionists, World of Impressionism, and Harvest of the Sun (Sarah, age 10,  gave four stars to this disc on the life and work of Van Gogh).
<p>
Music lessons and music appreciation are also available on CD-i. We only saw one: Mozart: A Musical Biography ($17.98). You can play it as a regular CD with lovely excerpts from Mozart's most famous pieces. Or view a biography of Mozart connected to the music, or slide shows about 10 different kinds of music (opera, chamber music, and early Renaissance, to name three). Again, the "game" is no big deal -- get with it, guys! Look at what Warner New Media has done for music appreciation on CD-ROM and do likewise.
<p>
A wide range of special-interest CD-i discs are also available. These are mostly how-tos, ranging from astrology, to stamp collecting, to sailing, to birdwatching. We happened to view Time-Life's excellent $49.98 disc on Photography. The 25 step-by-step workshops actually allow you to take photos with a simulated camera and see the hopefully glorious results onscreen. You learn how to set up your camera and accessories; how to use people, sports, landscape, and art in your photos; and how to handle lighting and composition. Ted, a tough customer if there ever was one, gave it four hearts when he reviewed it last year.
<p>
Philips has many more education titles planned for 1994. A sampling: Stickybear Early Learning, Stickybear Math, and Stickybear Spelling; a CD-i version of The New Grolier Electronic Encyclopedia; new titles featuring the Berenstain Bears, Hanna-Barbera cartoon characters, Shari Lewis's "Lamb Chop" character; and Mercer Mayer's "Little Monster At School," an interactive book created exclusively for CD-i.
<p>
Did I tell you about all the games you can play on CD-i? No, I didn't. Your humble reviewer didn't get any games to review-after all, we're an educational magazine! Suffice it to say that for $29.98 each you can play chess, battleship, 3-D tic-tac-toe, jigsaw, backgammon, or Go with your simulated CD-i opponent. Or play an adventure game, try out your skills as a racecar driver, goof off with Wacky Golf, or even play pinball.
<p>
Bottom line: CD-ROM has more versatility and more titles. For that reason, we would suggest it rather than CD-i for those who are unafraid of computers. Families with less money to spend, or who are computer phobic, or who want to ease their way into interactive education, or who want some of the specific programs mentioned above, will find CD-i has a lot to offer. 
<p>
<strong>Where to Find It</strong>
<p>
Optimum Resource, Inc.
5 Hiltech Lane
Hilton Head Island, SC 29926
Orders: (800) 327-1473
Inquiries: (803) 689-8000
Fax: (803) 689-8008
<p>
<hr>
<strong>COPYRIGHT INFORMATION</strong>
<br>Copyright 1994 Home Life Inc. 
<br>Originally published in Practical Homeschooling No. 5.
<br>All rights reserved. This article or any part of it may not be published on any Internet or WWW site, or any BBS, or any other electronic or print medium, or any other medium, without our expression written permission. To request permission, please fax 314-225-0743 and describe the article, where you would like to publish it, and how many people you expect to read your publication. We will get back to you with our response as soon as possible.
</body>

