<head><title>Info. Superhighway to Where?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFD0">
<center><h1>Information Superhighway to Where?</h1><br><strong>By Jason Rippetoe</strong></center>
<p><hr>
Jason Rippetoe is the father of two pre-homeschooled children and the founder of the Home School Online bulletin board network. You can reach him at HmeSchool@AOL,com or dial in anytime to his bulletin board. Ecclesia Online, at (510) 526-6584. Set your modem software to 8-N-1 and VT-100 or ANSI, and use the password and ID of "guest" when first logging on. You can also subscribe to two new home education newsgroups founded and moderated by Jason by sending the message "Subscribe" to hs.subscribe@servant.com. 
<hr>
<p>
To most people, the NII is only a vague idea about somehow merging their computer, telephone, and television into one big super-unit hooked up to cable wires. At this point, even those involved in constructing the NII aren't sure how they're going to bring everything together. 
<p>
What's certain is that big players in the entertainment, electronics, communications and commercial sectors are seeking to grab a piece of the action. There's a great deal of money to be made in the distribution of the type of services the NII is promising, and when there's money to be made things will get done for better or worse. While different companies may be proposing varied and often incompatible solutions of bringing the NII to every home in America, they will hammer out something eventually. The NII is taking shape as we speak.
<p>
What is the NII? Communications: high-speed transfer of electronic data over fiber optic strands at the speed of light. This data can consist of just about anything -- video, sound, photos, computer files, text, or a combination. In some ways it will provide the goodies currently available on multimedia CD-ROMs, but much faster and with far greater capabilities. 
<p>
All of the technology to make the NII a reality already exists. The only thing holding it back is the current state of the hardware. Not the computers; these are already powerful enough to perform many NII functions. What's strangling the NII are the thousands of miles of outdated copper wire that currently carry electronic signals into our homes. To make the NII a reality, without making it instantly obsolete, our homes must able to receive electronic data at speeds that copper wire can't handle. Either a nation-wide wireless network (like cellular phones or broadcast TV) or a fiber-optics network (laid out like regular telephone lines or cable TV) will have to be built. This is going to be a very expensive proposition no matter how you look at it. 
<p>
The NII promises big changes in the way America works, plays, and learns as all of our homes, businesses, and communities are wired for the NII technology. It also raises troubling questions about privacy, content, and control that should concern the homeschooling community. Like many technologies, promise and threat go hand-in-hand. The promise is of expanded educational opportunities for homeschooled children and youth. The threat is that Big Brother might, indeed, be watching you. 
<p>
Plan to wait and see just what develops? You'll be waiting until the turn of the century, when full-scale implementation of the NII is expected to be in place. Want to sneak a peek at what the future might be bringing to your door? Then take a look at the NII's precursor, the Internet. 
<p>
<strong>The Internet: On-Ramp to the Information Superhighway</strong>
<p>
What's the Internet? I'm glad you asked.
<p>
Before the Information Superhighway was even a gleam in Al Gore's eye, there was the Internet. Nobody called it that, of course. It all started, as many things do, with the government: the Department of Defense, to be exact. In the mid-1960s the DOD decided that they needed a way to keep their computer messaging system intact in case of a nuclear attack. This required a different way of dealing with information than previous network strategies could provide. So a system was designed that required no network hub, no need for centralized command, and no dependance on any single part. As long as any two machines on the network were still operating and the phone lines between them could carry information, the network would still be there for use in an emergency situation. 
<p>
The network, when it became a reality, was called ARPANet after the DOD's Advanced Research Projects Agency. In addition to its use by the DOD, ARPANet connected a number of larger research organizations in the government, academic, military, and commercial fields. 
<p>
It didn't take long for those within academic circles to see the value of being connected to other institutions. Over the next 10 years, as computers became more powerful and easier to use, the number of locations connected to the network grew, as did the number of users at each location. During that time, whole other networks hooked up to the backbone of ARPANet, and the "inter-network" -- the Internet -- was born. 
<p>
Technically, the Internet isn't a network. It provides the bridges between networks that allows the various networks to communicate. 
<p>
Making all these varied networks that make up the Internet work together was difficult. Anyone familiar with computers knows that a program written for one type of computer won't run on another type. For example, an IBM PC isn't able to run programs written for the Apple Macintosh and vice-versa. But a network of PCs can speak to a network of Macs because the networks have agreed to speak a common language -- a communications protocol called IP which stands for, creatively enough, Internet Protocol. Any machine that is connected by modem or cable to a network that is part of the Internet and runs a program that allows it to understand the IP is able to take advantage of Internet services. 
<p>
The actual lines that carry Internet information (the fiber optic backbone) are fast. Very fast. The original lines for ARPANet carried about 56,000 bits of computer information per second, roughly 50,000 words per minute. The main lines of today's Internet speed information at 45 million bits per second. Even that isn't fast enough to build the future. The peripheral networks that make up the Internet often run at much slower speeds, but then again, they don't handle quite the amount of traffic the main lines need to.
<p>
For years the Internet remained the private domain of big institutions with outsiders being limited to e-mail (electronic mail) access if anything at all, and that only through the big online services. All of that changed about two years ago when the National Science Foundation, a government agency that controls the high-speed backbone of the Internet, lifted restrictions against commercial use. This action opened the door for commercial outfits, called Internet Service Providers, to sell access to the Internet to private individuals. For the first time, anyone with a home computer and a modem could hook directly into the Internet and take advantage of the rich supply of resources available. So now the Internet is available to the common man. 
<p>
Who owns the Internet? Here's a surprise: nobody does! It just exists, grown far beyond the control of any one entity. There are over 100,000 registered Internet host sites around the world, and many more unregistered hosts (computers directly connected to the Internet), making the actual number difficult to estimate. 
<p>
A recent Time magazine article placed the number of Internet users at twenty million and growing by a million new users each month. Suddenly, the computer revolution seems to have taken hold, and online is the place to be. Online services like Compuserve, GEnie, Prodigy and America Online (all profiled in a previous issue of Practical Homeschooling) are booming and corporations such as Microsoft, Apple, and AT&T will shortly be getting into the online service business as well. 
<p>
All of the big services currently offer Internet e-mail. Many will shortly be offering full Internet access and hopefully making the Internet easier to use.
<p>
<strong>What's Out There?</strong>
<p>
What sort of resources does the Internet offer? For starters, imagine that you're doing a unit study on space. So you call up your Internet provider, telnet (more on that later) to one of NASA's Internet sites, and search around their database for educational items. Not only will you find information about the food that astronauts eat, but you'll find that other educators have been there before you and left complete lesson plans on the subject. All you have to do is transfer the information to your home computer. While you're at it, you can pick up digitized photos from the space shuttle of a hurricane for that weather study you plan to start next month. 
<p>
Or perhaps you need a copy of one of Shakespeare's works, the Magna Carta, Lincoln's Inaugural address, or even a copy of the King James Bible. Send a file transfer request to the Gutenberg Project, and in seconds you've received the file you wanted. 
<p>
When your older child begins her study of chemistry, she might find it helpful to be a regular visitor to the edu.chemistry.discussion newsgroup where she can leave typed messages that others will read and respond to. If she has more detailed questions, perhaps she can do an Internet Relay Chat session -- the online equivalent of a telephone call using keyboards instead of voices -- to interact with someone with more knowledge in a particular area. 
<p>
Internet e-mail arrives very shortly after it's sent, almost instantaneously in some cases. This is a boon if you're interested in practicing a foreign language or studying geography the fun way. Your son can send messages to electronic pen-pals across the country or on the other side of the globe, getting to meet and "talk" with other children in different countries without the wait associated with slow international mail delivery schedules. 
<p>
Perhaps you're wondering about how to increase your child's aptitude for reading. You can connect to the the government's ERIC database and do a search that will pull up relevant articles in no time. There are also online adventure games that can be played in real-time, including one designed for children based on L. Frank Baum's Oz stories. There are also some designed by children. One that I'd like to explore someday recreates the Narnia of C.S. Lewis' fantasy tales.
<p>
The Internet includes many other resources . . . if you know where to look. The Internet was forged by institutions of higher learning and much of it has an educational bent that can be exploited by the online homeschooler. With a little patience and a sense of adventure, you can discover educational resources you had no idea were available. 
<p>
Many books have been written about the Internet. With all there is to learn, you could fill a fat twenty-volume set. But you don't need to do everything right off. That's one of the joys of learning the Internet -- exploring what you can with the basics and picking up new information and skills as you go. 
<p>
<strong>An Overview of Internet Services</strong>
<p>
One of the nice things about the Internet is that people online tend to be very helpful. Almost all of them had similar questions as "newbies" to the net and there are extensive FAQ (frequently asked questions) files on just about every Internet feature. This isn't the place to answer all of the questions, but I will give a short description of some of the most commonly used features and Internet necessities.
<p>
<strong>Addressed for Success.</strong> It all starts with an address. That's the first necessity. An Internet address is like the address that's printed on a letter that comes to your home, with a few differences. The information in the address shows who it goes to and where to find them. An Internet address takes the form of four sets of numbers separated by periods like this: 1234.56.7.8, a format that doesn't lend itself to easy memorization, so we humans can use a different form without having to deal with all those numbers. The form for us is this: name@somewhere.domain. The "domain" part is an indication of what type of system the "somewhere" is. One of my e-mail addresses is hmeschool@aol.com, which tells the Internet to deliver the message to the account called "hmeschool" on the system America Online (aol) which is a commercial carrier (com). Names can be longer and more specific as well. To reach someone at the Whole Earth 'Lectronic Link in the San Francisco Bay Area, you'd address it to name@well.sf.ca.us. Deciphering that one is pretty easy -- it's very similar to a standard street address. Others can be more obscure. The major difference between electronic and paper mail addresses is that if you have a transposed number or misspelled name on paper mail it still has a chance of getting where it's supposed to. With electronic addresses it's another story altogether. If you leave out one letter or put a character in the wrong place, your mail or action will be "bounced," the electronic version of a "return to sender, address unknown" stamp.
<p>
<strong>E-mail.</strong> Electronic mail is the most commonly used of any Internet feature, linking together millions of people. It's the feature that most people are familiar with. If you are part of an online service like Prodigy and you send an e-mail message to someone on another service, say, Compuserve; you use the Internet to do it. Many people use the Internet in this way without even knowing that they're doing so. 
<p>
E-mail is just what its name implies, a counterpart to regular paper mail. Instead of writing it out longhand, however, you type your message into the computer. There's no envelope, and no stamp -- instead of dropping the finished letter or message into a mailbox for pickup, a few keystrokes or a click of the mouse button sends the mail on its way. 
<p>
E-mail's greatest advantage is speed. Just as the advent of the locomotive made the previously "speedy" Pony Express seem slow, so has e-mail speed changed the face of mail. E-mail can arrive almost instantaneously, instead of the days associated with paper mail. Even overnight mail can't match the speed of e-mail. 
<p>
This isn't to say that e-mail will replace the more solid type, as it's hard to send some types of documents by e-mail. But the speed and convenience of e-mail is a definite advantage over the paper kind, and for some strange reason, people you write to by e-mail are more likely to write back!
<p>
<strong>Telnet.</strong> The Internet protocol for remote terminal connection is called telnet. What "remote terminal connection" means is that a kid in Iowa can use his modem to call his local Internet provider, which allows him to connect to an Internet computer in Florida (or Paris for that matter) and use that computer as if he was sitting in front of it. Telnetting around is one of the most interesting things that you can do on the Internet, exploring the far-flung systems of the world. Once you connect to these systems the things you can do varies from site to site. At some you can read various newsgroups (explained below). At others you can scan extensive databases on specialized subjects such as chemistry, astronomy, or the social sciences. At many, you can transfer files to your home computer using FTP, such as the NASA site mentioned in the example above.
<p>
What some consider a drawback to telnet exploration is that you need to learn new ways to get around. Because telnet allows you to operate the remote computer as if you were sitting in front of it, you have to use commands that that particular computer understands. On one system, you might use the dreaded Unix command-line interface in which you type short commands to make the system do what you want. Another system might present you with a menu with choices highlighted. You just type in a letter corresponding to a menu choice and you're on your way. Because of this wide difference in computer types and command structures, some telnet sites are more user-friendly than others. But don't be put off by the challenge of learning a new system. You may have to do a little digging, but as we all know, sometimes the things worth having are worth going through a little trouble for!
<p>
<strong>Mailing Lists.</strong> When people on the Internet have a common interest, they often form a mailing list to keep up to date on new developments in their field of interest. Interested individuals contribute items that they think others on the list will find useful, be it news items, commentary, personal experiences or updates and send them to the mailing list moderator. At a preset time (daily, weekly, monthly, or occasionally) the moderator forwards copies of all of the items contributed to others on the list. There are mailing lists for just about everything imaginable: model rocketry, politics, health concerns, hobbies and, yes, even homeschooling. 
<p>
There are currently two homeschool mailing lists that I know of; one for general information (home-ed-request@think.com) and the other for political matters (home-ed-politics-request@mainstream.com). You can subscribe to either or both of these by sending an e-mail message to their Internet addresses with the word "Subscribe" in the body of the message. Very shortly, the four conferences of the Homeschool Online Network will be available as a mailing list as well.
<p>
<strong>Usenet.</strong> Usenet, or netnews, is the reverse of a mailing list. A mailing list comes to you; but you have to go to a newsgroup! 
<p>
Internet newsgroups are like electronic meeting halls. When a user enters a newsgroup, he is presented with a list of messages posted by other users that he can read and respond to. When he next checks the newsgroup, he may find that others have responded to his response to others, and in this way an ongoing discussion is maintained. 
<p>
Like mailing lists, there are thousands of newsgroups and it would be surprising if someone were unable to find something of interest. A recent list I obtained had over 5,000 newsgroups listed and began with the words, "This list is far from complete," which gives an idea of the scope you've got to deal with. Often the problem is of having too many choices; you should pick and choose carefully!
<p>
<strong>FTP.</strong> If you're going to use the Internet, you'd better get used to acronyms, because they're everywhere. This particular one stands for "File Transfer Protocol," the method that the Internet uses to send files from one computer to another. An "ftp site" is a depository for items that can be ftp-ed. For instance, when getting a copy of the Magna Carta or a digitized photo of a hurricane from the Internet, it is most likely that the actual transfer would be done through ftp. 
<p>
Ftp has a set of commands that you use to have the ftp site transfer the file to your Internet provider, from which you can download it to your home computer. The types of files available include text, sounds, digitized video and photos, public distributable software, and other items. 
<p>
If it can be turned into digital signals, it's somewhere on the Internet. Someone has even gone to the effort to digitize the entire Frank Capra movie It's a Wonderful Life and make it available for your downloading pleasure. (If you really want to see it, you'd be better off renting it. Most home system hard drives couldn't hold the whole thing!)
<p>
<strong>archie.</strong> Closely connected to ftp is archie. This tool (always spelled with lowercase letters despite the conventions of grammar!) is what you use to find the files you want to ftp. Tell archie what you're looking for and if it's out there, he'll find it and tell you where to ftp it from. Without archie, you'd have to telnet to an ftp site and manually scroll through hundreds of file listings to find what you want-not a fun thing to do. archie makes finding files quick and painless.
<p>
<strong>Gopher.</strong> No, not the furry rodent or the purser on the old Love Boat TV series. Gopher is an attempt to make the Internet easier to use. It's what's called a client/server system. That means that on your home machine you run a special program that gives you an interface similar to that of your home computer. If you run a PC with Windows, Gopher looks like Windows. On a Macintosh it looks like a Macintosh. Gopher automates many of the repetitive tasks associated with hunting for information on the net and make the entire process much easier. Gopher still uses all of the basic Internet functions; it just hides them behind a computer application so you don't have to deal with them face to face.
<p>
<strong>WWW.</strong>WWW stands for the World Wide Web, also known as W3. WWW is the new kid on the Internet block and an ambitious one at that! What WWW is and is becoming is a "distributable hypertext system." It's kind of hard to explain, but I'll give it a shot. Like Gopher, WWW is a client/server program. It integrates most of the features of Gopher and can actually use Gopher to do things on the network. What makes it different from Gopher is the "hypertext" bit. If you call up a WWW document on a subject, it provides you with text that has certain portions highlighted. As you're reading through the text, if you find something that's highlighted that interests you, a click from the mouse will bring up a link with more information. For example, If you're reading through a text that covers the history of printing, you might find a highlighted portion about Benjamin Franklin. Selecting that portion might bring up a woodcut of Franklin or a list of other available information on his life. Clicking on a highlighted portion about photocopiers might bring up a diagram showing how photocopying works. Hypertext links can also bring up sounds or animations. 
<p>
For now, WWW looks like the future of the Internet, and a lot of people are excited about it. Usage of WWW services at the WWW founding site is growing at twice the rate of the Internet itself. The WWW will be watched closely as the NII gets closer, and probably provides the first glimpse of what navigating the NII will be like. The WWW system can access anything served by gopher, ftp, Usenet, anything accessible through telnet, and other Internet features. 
<p>
<strong>Future Perfect?</strong>
<p>
What of the future? George Guilder, conservative theorist and author, has said in his book Life After Television that the advent of the telecomputer (his term for the combining of telephones and multimedia computers which is what the NII promises) will have a radical effect on education. Gilder thinks telecomputers will encourage educational competition and make homeschooling more attractive and possible. He also foresees local "micro-schools" in which neighborhood children gather to learn social skills. Each such school would only need a modem hookup to bring the best teachers in the world into its classrooms. Running such a school would not be beyond the scope of a church, support group, or other community organization. This means the public schools would either have to put up (improve their teaching and start mollifying parents by moving away from the current radical agenda) or shut up (go out of business).
<p>
While the type of homeschooling that Gilder is speaking of may be somewhat different than my idea of home-based education, and replacing public education with community-based micro-schools might not be as easy as Gilder supposes, his comments do reveal his belief that the NII will have a strong focus on educational endeavors. Conceivably anyone educating at home will be able to take advantage of online (and constantly updated) encyclopedias, easily obtain educational materials, and easyily access experts and persons with similar interests. 
<p>
NII visionaries have proposed some of the following ideas. For example, your son may take part in an interactive physics lesson that adapts itself to his responses and works with difficult concepts on a level he understands by testing his current knowledge. Or he can specially request video documentaries on any subject by typing in a few keystrokes. If your daughter is interested in meteorology, live information from weather satellites and the National Weather Service will be instantly available, as well as a storehouse of weather-related texts and tools. Help with difficult academic subjects will be available from online databases and tutoring services. Prerecorded sound and video files dealing with your child's problem will be instantly available, and if it's a new problem, the solution, when found, will be saved in the database for the next person who asks the same question. There will also be entire encyclopedias on a wide variety of reference subjects that adapt the information displayed for the level of understanding of the person who requests it. A brief overview or in-depth information will be instantly available with abundant cross-references and diagrams, animation, photographs, recordings, video, and text. "You want Richard Nixon's resignation speech? Will that be text, video, or sound, sir?" Eventually, the emerging virtual reality technology will find a comfortable home on the NII. If you want to explore the workings of an internal combustion engine, just strap on your goggles and walk around inside one. If you tire of that, travel the arteries of the human body or climb the mountains of Mars in realistic looking 3-D.
<p>
<strong>Or Future Imperfect?</strong>
<p>
The possibilities are vast. But along with the promises come new threats to individual privacy and freedom. It is easy to be tempted by technology; or, as Jacques Ellul would say, seduced. When we hear all of the promises, it's easy to forget the threats in our excitement. Western society has never handled technology well; it's unlikely that the track record will change when the NII becomes a reality. 
<p>
In his book The Church at the End of the Twentieth Century, the late Dr. Francis Schaeffer spoke of how modern technology has been used to manipulate people. When it comes to computers, the threat increases. He says, "The computer has entered a new age -- it can watch you. The great eye can be upon you from your birth to your death . . . The existence of the computer and the control it puts into the hands of those in power steps up the power of each of the forms of modern manipulation in the hands of the manipulators." 
<p>
Schaeffer is correct. Along with the Information Superhighway's benefits comes potential for all manner of electronic surveillance and manipulation. For example, it was recently revealed that the FBI wants to monitor your calling patterns and credit card transactions. The Feds are pushing for an NII design that will allow them to easily eavesdrop. That's what all the brouhaha about the Clipper Chip is about. It's a government-endorsed form of encryption which the government can crack. To date the Clinton administration has supported the Clipper Chip, and sought to ban alternative -- and more powerful -- encryption technologies which would allow you to send electronic messages the government couldn't read.
<p>
How should we as Christians respond to such potential for monitoring? Some think we should become neo-Luddites. If we don't actually smash the new technology as those 19th century textile workers did, at least they think we should refuse to use it. I respond, rather, that we should carefully onsider new technology and how it might affect us before uncritically adopting it. We should also consider how we might utilize it to counteract the manipulation that Schaeffer describes. 
<p>
It is my belief that the Information Superhighway has equal potential as a source of disinformation and a source of information. There are many Big Brother-ish opportunities for surveillance of information, as noted above. The NII might also continue the current bottleneck of news that afflicts the major news sources on television and radio. The corporations who will own and sponsor the NII are likely to provide a "more of the same" serving of sound bites and fluff that is called news but is only designed to keep the attention of viewers long enough to get an advertisement in front of their faces. 
<p>
There is also the Hollywood factor. Hollywood has taught us to value image above substance. Even in presidential politics image takes the drivers' seat. In a face-to-face debate, a well-groomed person with wonderful enunciation and a few good jokes can demolish someone who has a stronger argument if that person looks disheveled. Remember the Kennedy-Nixon TV debates? (If you don't, wait a couple of years and download it from the NII!)
<p>
Right now the Internet is heavily loaded with content, not image. When all you've got to battle with is the written word, you stand or fall with what you write. In that sense the text-based Internet of today is an equalizer -- there is nothing for people to see. They are forced to deal with your words and the arguments within. How will this change when the NII is implemented and arguments are presented in multimedia extravaganzas? Will the image (and therefore the argument) of the person producing a marvelous presentation be enhanced while our poor text-based friend is ignored? Will online services hire Hollywood starlets to croon, "Welcome, big boy!" to you when you log on? Will database providers have to license cartoon characters to entice you to sign up? Will we have Nike Online and Madonna Modems? Will keyboards be replaced with remote controls, so couch potatoes can access the NII without having to contribute anything to the discussion? Will there be discussions, or just millions of cartoons, movies, and phony polls designed to flush out potential buyers of Florida condos? Time will tell.
<p>
In addition to these issues, there's one more thing: morality. Already in the world of computer bulletin board systems (BBSs) many of the most profitable exist solely for the distribution of digitized pornography and raunchy real-time chat. Will the NII be similarly endowed? What options will exist for those of us who would like to take advantage of educational opportunities for our children without exposing them to harmful material? I regularly warn parents who are exploring going online to monitor their children's usage of online systems and BBSs. I suspect that the situation with the NII will warrant similar warnings.
<p>
The NII promises access to information, but while there is much to be said for information, not all information is good or right or true. Information is not knowledge, and knowledge is not wisdom. Knowledge is information that has been appropriated and understood within the overall context of local and world events, society in general, and the world of ideas. Wisdom is putting that knowledge to good use. 
<p>
<strong>Why Homeschoolers Should Get Wired</strong>
<p>
To close this off, I'd like to propose some ways in which current online technology can be a useful source of information for homeschooling families that does not depend on the support of mainstream media institutions. My first thought comes from observations of the recent HR6 situation, in which a bill with potential for damage to homeschools was amended due to quick action from the homeschool community. The initial trumpet call came from the Home School Legal Defense Association via a document faxed to homeschool support groups and magazines. It would seem that the online world would provide a ready forum for such emergencies. After a sort, that's what happened. On America Online, a discussion folder about HR6 garnered some 90 messages in a day and a half -- an unheard-of happening in the homeschool area. The folder revealed there was initially a good degree of misunderstanding on the issue -- misunderstandings which were rapidly cleared up by people "in the know" posting the facts. 
<p>
While it's clear that it is impossible to eliminate all misunderstanding, steps can be taken that minimize them. Much of the time and cost to HSLDA to fax such urgent messages could easily be avoided if homeschool leaders were all wired to the Internet. By compiling an Internet mailing list of people interested in being informed of urgent matters in this manner, thousands of people could be informed with just a few keystrokes and without long distance phone charges. Those people could in turn print out copies of the information and distribute it widely by fax and photocopy to homeschool support groups and others.
<p>
Such services need not be confined to emergency information either. It is possible to establish a similar, regularly distributed "alternative news service" that includes other issues and happenings of concern to homeschooling families. In true mailing-list style, articles and news items could be forwarded to a moderator who compiles them and distributes them in a timely manner. When faced with a media establishment that is often hostile to our way of life, it would be a legitimate and useful service for circumventing normal biased news channels. 
<p>
Finally, I propose that a free grassroots network of independent BBSs be established for the homeschooling community and other interested parties by those within the homeschooling community. This network should serve as a source of information and assistance for homeschooling families to fulfill their ministry to their children. I would like to see it take advantage of whatever technology is available, but not be tied to any one type. Like the network the Department of Defense proposed that spawned the Internet, it should be able to take a few hits and not collapse. Such a network would not blaze any new trails -- tested, tried, and inexpensive technology to establish such an electronic network has already been available for many years. In doing so, we should not look to over-burden organizations like HSLDA to provide the leadership, but instead take the initiative ourselves. That's the line I'm trying to follow with Homeschool Online Network, and it's finally beginning to gather speed.
<p>
If we look to the future, we will not stumble into it unknowingly. While the emerging technologies threaten to provide government and Big Business with greater control over our lives due to the emerging technologies, those same technologies can work in our favor. there are many possibilities for the future and it's hard to make predictions. Regardless of what the future holds we should take whatever steps that are within our power to provide our children with better access to information and to strengthen the extended homeschool community. After all, it's not just the future, it's our future.
<p>
<hr>
