</DOCHDR>
<head><title>How Do I Choose a Computer?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFD0">
<center><h1>How Do I Choose a Computer?</h1><br><strong>By Dan and Tammy Kihlstadius</strong></center>
<p><hr>
Dan and Tammy Kihlstadius are frequent contributors to our "Computer Room" section. They homeschool all their children while simultaneously owning and managing the Home Computer Market. Send them your software and hardware questions at PO Box 385377, Bloomington, MN 55438, (612) 844-0462.
<hr><p>
Computer shopping for the first time? Then get a tight grip on your wallet and watch out -- things are not always what they seem!
<p>
At first glance, the advertised "low, low bargain price" makes it seem your best choice is a low-end IBM-compatible. But there are some things that you will want to find out about that system before the purchase, not when it is too late, after you already own it.
<p>
When you tell the salesman what you are looking for, you will probably be told that the "complete system less than $1,000" bargain package system is "okay" and will run many DOS-based programs. The store's ad has done its job; it got you in the door. They make next to nothing if you buy this system, so now comes the sale pitch.
<p>
"The video monitor that comes with this discount package is the cheapest, lowest quality available, so you really should consider something that will have crisper details and will be easier on your eyes, especially for those small children of yours." Add $100-$200.
<p>
"Two meg of RAM is enough memory to run many programs, but the best software requires four meg or more, especially if you want to run Windows, which, if you are a newer computer user, you will need."  Buy more RAM. Add another $150-$200.
<p>
"And, of course, if you really want to take advantage of the cutting edge of technology, you'll want a CD-ROM drive." Add $250 and up.
<p>
So you take home what you thought was going to be a bargain-priced PC system, now at $600 higher, only to find out that all the add-ons were not the end of what you needed. Your computer still can't reproduce speech that resembles anything human (more like a robot with a low I.Q.!) The cheapest radio you can buy probably produces better musical sound. So you add a sound board. Add $75 to $150.
<p>
Are you through yet? Nooooo! Today's best and fanciest programs produce complex graphics that literally "choke" the video circuitry of most cheaper and mid-range priced computers. This will be especially true of most programs coming out in the future. You add a one meg video RAM board. Add $75-$100.
<p>
Now your computer will finally run the best educational programs -- all for a mere $850+ more than you thought this bargain-priced system was going to cost you.
<p>
Know all the hidden costs before you make your purchase. Although the initial cost of a Macintosh is higher than an IBM-compatible, most of these added components are included. Newer versions of Macintosh also include a built-in CD-ROM.
<p>
<strong>"What kind of computer should I buy?"</strong>
<p>
When we discuss "kinds" of computers, we are not referring to brands of computers, but what type of system runs the programs on the computer. Of all the different types of computers, there are really only two types to consider for home use -- Macintosh (Mac) and IBM-type (also known as PCs or IBM-compatible clones). 
<p>
PCs are the most popular in the corporate world. Consequently, since most computers used in the world are used in corporations, most of the computers made are PCs. So if you were going to purchase a computer for a corporation or to run a commercial business, we would suggest an IBM-compatible PC clone. If your primary need for a computer is to run specialized software that can only run on a PC, buy a PC.
<p>
However, since you are reading this to help you choose a computer for your home school, those uses probably don't apply to you for your planned computer needs. If your primary uses are going to be educational, and/or personal home use, you will want to strongly consider a Macintosh as your best choice.
<p>
<strong>"So what's the difference?"</strong>
<p>
In order to understand why to chose one type of computer over the other, or what the differences are all about, you need to understand the differences in the way the two operate. As one major PC magazine says, "If you wanted easy-to-use software or access to lots of graphics applications (word processing, newsletters, flyers, etc.), you bought Macintoshes. If you wanted compatibility with a larger number of systems (hooking up your computer with a bunch of other computers-like they do in large businesses) and access to a greater number of software packages, you bought DOS or Windows-based PCs."
<p>
At first glance, Windows looks like a Mac. In fact, it is intentionally designed to imitate a Mac. The best way to describe it is that Windows is similar to a Mac. Most PC salesmen will try to tell you that Windows makes a PC as easy to use as a Mac, but this is simply not true. It takes a significant amount of time and know-how to set up on your system. Yes, using Windows is far easier than using DOS, but if you try to name a file, add capabilities, or update your system software, you're right back to the MS-DOS commands that Windows was supposed to eliminate. You still need a working knowledge of MS-DOS to set up programs under Windows. Windows programs take up to twice as much disk space and run noticeably slower than the equivalent program on a Macintosh.
<p>
While on the subject of computer myths, let me dispel the myth that software is not available for Macintoshes. It is true that most stores primarily carry PC software, with only a small Mac section. This is because most Mac software is sold mail-order. If you want it, there is plenty of it out there to be bought.
<p>
Another myth is that children should learn how to use MS-DOS-based PCs because that is what they will be using out in the "real-world job marketplace." Within five years or less, MS-DOS as we know it will basically be extinct in the real business and corporate world. The "powers that be" that run the real computer world are spending millions of dollars developing new ways of operating computers that will make the PCs of tomorrow look, more than anything else, like the Mac of today.
<p>
Not all educational programs can take advantage of the Windows or GUI environment on a PC, while every Macintosh program does so automatically. This is one of the reasons Macintosh computers are known within the computer industry as being far more "user friendly" than PCs. A Macintosh is operated by moving an arrow on the screen with a "mouse" to each command and clicking on it. Moving between programs is done with the mouse, not with coded words and obscure, cryptic commands, as with a DOS-operated PC. Once you learn the proper keyboard commands, you are also able to use the keyboard to enter commands, similar to a DOS computer. 
<p>
A Macintosh is so easy to master that even a four-year-old pre-reader can learn to open and run his or her own programs without help. If they can, you can.
<p>
<strong>"How do I plan to use this tool?"</strong>
<p>
If you plan to run a home business with your computer, unless you need specialized software for your business, a Mac can handle business and accounting applications as well as a PC. Either a Mac or a PC can be a great asset in controlling your personal finances. There are wonderful programs that allow you to do detailed budgeting painlessly. The one we use and love is Quicken, from Intuit (PO Box 3014, Menlo Park, CA 94026).
<p>
It is generally accepted that Macintosh is the hands-down winner for desktop publishing. Nothing beats a Mac for producing professional looking newsletters, brochures, letters, catalogs, etc. This magazine was produced solely on Macintoshes!
<p>
If you are concerned about appealing to an auditory learner, or any learner for that matter, the Mac will play phonics and speech more accurately than a PC. Sound and video capabilities are built into every Mac.
<p>
Lastly, a Macintosh is designed to be accessible to users with disabilities. Every Macintosh comes with Easy Access, Sticky Keys, Slow Keys, Close View, and Mouse Keys. 
<p>
<strong>"What is my prior computer experience?"</strong>
<p>
Practical Homeschooling suggests that unless you have significant experience with the PC and MS-DOS world, you should get a Macintosh. If you buy a PC, be prepared to learn the equivalent of a second language and spend a lot of time studying manuals. I have been told that it takes well over 100 hours of learning/training to be able to fluently use a PC!
<p>
Husbands, consider your wife's computer experience. We hear many horror stories from wives of computer-wizard husbands that buy a PC, set it in front them, and say, "Here, use this in your home school!" 
<p>
Husbands, unless you are willing teach your wife how to use MS-DOS, buy a Macintosh. With a Mac, she would be using the computer and getting results instead of being overcome by computerphobia.
<p>
I do understand that there are times that a PC is necessary. If so, buy a PC. Both kinds of computers are available for that very reason. Just be aware, in advance, of the learning curve.
<p>
The difference in learning curve  between a Macintosh and a PC can be summarized in this way: it's like the difference between learning to drive an automatic car and learning to fly an airplane. If you doubt this, ask any mother who owns a computer!  
<p>
<strong>"How much should I budget for a computer?"</strong>
<p>
You can get the hottest new computer system for about 1/3 of what it would have cost just two years ago! You can buy a very nice entry level computer for around $1,300 to $1,500. A bare-bones system capable of running most educational software can be found for less than $1,000. And if you're thinking of buying a used system, there are even more bargains! A beginner used system can be purchased for less than $700.
<p>
A Mac costs about 10-25 percent more than a PC clone. However, a Mac has built-in features that cost extra on a PC. Also, the graphics and sound are noticeably better. Lastly, a Mac has lower costs of ownership over a 5-year period. A study comparing Macintosh, DOS, Windows, and OS/2 systems added up hardware, software, training, and support costs up over a 5-year period and found Mac to be 19 percent cheaper than a Windows-based system, and even a better bargain than that compared to the other systems in the study!
<p>
Most newer PCs and all new Macs are designed not to become obsolete in the near future-they both offer "upgrade paths." This means that you can add on or upgrade to faster, bigger, and newer parts for a moderate price.
<p>
<strong>"What size computer should I get?" </strong>
<p>
Choosing from all the PC clones can be very confusing. Performance, configuration, and quality can vary greatly from manufacturer to manufacturer. Of all the things to consider, the two most important factors are speed and storage capacity (both hard drive and RAM memory).
<p>
If you choose an IBM or PC clone, get at least a 386SX. A 486 is better. Never buy one smaller than a 286 (such as 8088 or 8086). Pay close attention to this: many older, cheaper, used computers have computer "brains" (CPUs or chips) smaller than 286. Don't buy them! The owner is selling it because he can't run most of the new software and you won't be able to, either! If the owner can't tell what kind/size of chip it is, again, don't buy it! If you can't afford a cheap, used, bare-bones 386 for around $500-$700 (including monitor and hard drive), you might want to seriously think about waiting until you can. 
<p>
If you can afford it, get at least 25 MHz with a minimum of 4 megabytes internal RAM and at least an 80 meg hard drive. Ideally, you should have more RAM memory (8 meg) to run Windows or Multimedia CDs, and a 100 meg or larger hard drive for your permanent memory storage.
<p>
Choosing a Mac is easier. It all boils down to how much speed and memory storage you can afford. Almost every other feature is standard on all Macs. If you choose a Macintosh, a Performa 550 or a Mac LC III is recommended. Both of these will have at least 4 megabytes internal RAM and a 80 meg or larger hard drive. If you can afford it, the Centris 610 (15 to 25 percent more than an LC III) is the best value combination of price and speed (it's twice as fast as an LC III).
<p>
Buy a 14-inch Super-VGA (Video Graphics Array) or RGB (Red, Green, Blue) non-interlaced color monitor (less flicker and easier on the eyes than an interlaced monitor) with about a .30 mm dot pitch or better with either a Mac or PC. Never buy a new one with a "dot pitch" larger than .30; .28 or lower is recommended. 
<p>
<strong>"What is a CD-ROM?"</strong>
<p>
Imagine having instant access to a mini-library whenever your studies take you into an unexplored research area. Imagine being able to access everything in those volumes on your chosen topic in minutes or even seconds. But imagine, finally, that your "library" takes up no more space than a shoebox!!
<p>
You are probably familiar with the wonderful stereo qualities of a CD (compact disc) and a CD player. The same technology works on a CD-ROM drive. The information is stored on the disk and read by laser beams. The CD-ROM drive can usually read audio-only CDs as well as the many multimedia reference and educational works available. 
<p>
Owning a CD-ROM drive opens doors to a whole new world of informational and educational resources. Because of a CD-ROM's enormous memory capacity (up to 600 megabytes or 300,000 book pages), you can have an entire encyclopedia at your fingertips. Type in "moon landings" or "Apollo" and it will display all its data on this subject. This is where the real fun starts. Not only does the encyclopedia provide the textual (written) information, it adds sound and colorful video clips. You don't just read about Neil Armstrong, you see him and hear his famous moon landing quote. This is what multimedia computing is all about!
<p>
A few words of caution before heading out to buy this hot technology: older CD-ROM drives are extremely slow. Happily, prices of the newer double-speed drives have been dropping rapidly these past few months. Do not settle for less than a double-speed, multisession-capable CD-ROM drive. Make sure it comes with the software needed to run it on your computer (Mac driver software does not work on PCs, and vice versa).
<p>
You need a double-spin drive to be compatible with the new MPC-2 standard (in the IBM-compatible world). Cutting-edge games are or will be MPC-2-compliant, to give you more speed, bigger video, and better animation. Most education discs do not require MPC-2-in fact, we can't think of any that do -- but the extra speedy access time is worthwhile. Also, it is rumored that you will be able to add a hardware upgrade to an MPC-2 drive and be able to play Video CDs on your computer monitor (if you care about such things). 
<p>
Triple-spin drives (from NEC) and quadra-spin drives (from Pioneer) are now available as well. These work just fine but are pricey for the home market. Desktop professionals, however, might be interested. This issue of Practical Homeschooling was laid out with the help of a quadra-spin "jukebox" drive. 
<p>
<strong>Summary</strong>
<p>
If you have no significant computer background and you are looking for a computer primarily for home use (personal finances, educational use, on-line services, word processing, desktop publishing, or a home-based business) a Macintosh may be the best computer for you. If you have a specific purpose for needing a PC, or have some background of prior PC usage, you may want a PC. If you can, talk to moms who are already using a computer at home, and ask how they feel about their choice of computer.
<p>
We hope we've helped you better understand computers and their differences, and helped you toward making some wiser decisions! 
<p>
<hr>
