<head><title>Comdex Report</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFD0">
<center><h1>Comdex Report</h1><br><strong>By Steve Waibel</strong></center>
<p><hr>
The fall Comdex convention, held in Las Vegas, is the largest trade show in the USA. Approximately 190,000 people attended the 1994 fall Comdex-and PHS was there! 
<p>
Knowing its size does not prepare you for the enormous size of this computer show. The convention is held in three different convention centers. It would take three straight days of looking at exhibits just to see them all, not taking into account the many conferences that are also offered.
<p>
Nearly every major computer company that you can think of was at the show. The biggest push this year was 32-bit operating systems, with IBM promoting their OS/2 WARP and Microsoft pumping for the still unreleased Windows 95 (former code name: Chicago). Intel and Apple were also heavily promoting Pentium and Power PC respectively.
<p>
Keynote speakers this year featured the richest man in the United States -- Microsoft founder and CEO Bill Gates -- plus the CEOs of major chip manufacturer Intel, and networking pioneer Novell. Nearly a hundred specialized conferences were geared for computer professionals on subjects such as networking, CD-ROM publishing, programming, and system design. 
<p>
<strong>To Market, To Market</strong>
<p>
With so many companies competing with each other, gimmicks galore were used to try to attract attention to their products. Klingons and Egyptian Princesses were running booths. Comedy acts drew big crowds to their sponsors' locations. Other companies hired celebrities, such as John Tesh from Entertainment Tonight and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, the retired NBA great, to sign autographs. Most companies set up computers so you could try out their new software or hardware. Bigger booths also had a theater area with wide screens for demonstrating their new software. Typically the demonstrations lasted about ten minutes with a drawing at the end to make sure people stayed for the entire thing.
<p>
<strong>Talk to Your Monitor</strong>
<p>
One conference we attended starred the upper management of companies such as Apple, IBM, and Borland, discussing the technology they thought would be coming in the near future. The hottest future technology, in their estimation, is voice recognition. Although some programs already feature voice recognition, the current technology has a lot of flaws. Generally a voice-recognition program can only recognize a limited number of words, and you must speak much slower than normal. 
<p>
Top software execs expect a vast improvement in the technology. Within the next two years, you should be able to just talk to your computer. 
<p>
This could make a great difference in children's software. For example: a child will speak words in an English lesson and the computer will be able to tell if the word was pronounced correctly. Foreign language software will be able to quiz you orally and correct your accent. Kids who hate to write, or who are too young to write, will write stories just by talking to the computer!
<p>
<strong>"Be Seeing You!"</strong>
<p>
If you have a modem, you can "chat" to a friend (via typed messages) or send them a file, but not at the same time. That's going to change. One of the advanced technologies being displayed at Comdex was the ability to transmit voice and data at the same time. Imagine taking a picture that your child has just drawn and sending it to Grandma. While your child is talking to Grandma, the picture appears on her screen. 
<p>
Another rapidly-advancing area is videoconferencing. In the most common implementation of this technology, your computer has a video camera mounted on it. The video signal is sent over the phone lines or over a network. Each person with a video camera-equipped computer can see the other and talk back and forth, albeit with small and jerky video. The reason the picture is small and jerky (only 3 frames are transmitted per minute over standard phone lines) is because the phone lines are not yet capable of handling huge amounts of data at fast speeds. However, the new ISDN (Integrated Services Digital Network) standard, once implemented, will make full-motion video-conferencing a reality. ISDN transforms ordinary tele-phone  (analog) lines into digital lines that can simultaneously carry both voice and images. This will make it possible, at least in theory, for you to attend and interact with a Harvard college lecture from your armchair in Dubuque, Iowa.  	
<p>
ISDN technology will finally provide the video phone that we have been told about for years (remember the videophone call in 2001: A Space Odyssey?). George Orwell also prophesied this technology in his grim 1984. In Orwell's book, two-way videoconferencing was used to maintain total control of people's lives -- "Big Brother Is Watching You!" However, our freedoms can not be challenged this way until just about everyone owns a computer with an installed video camera, and plenty of people, from the left to the right, are already agitating for privacy restrictions to prevent any such misuse of the technology. (In the meantime, using the "OFF" button can keep the video camera from observing your every move, and the truly paranoid can hang their jackets over it.) 
<p>
Presently used almost exclusively for corporate distance learning applications, with a price of several thousand per computer, videoconferencing will take a while to become mainstream. However, America Online will be testing ISDN access later this year, and PHS is already at work trying to put together a homeschool online university with classes for all ages, so tomorrow may arrive sooner than we think!
<p>
<strong>Encyclopedia Wars</strong>
<p>
In America we have the Cola Wars, the Pizza Wars . . . and now the Encyclopedia Wars. You probably have seen advertisements for Compton's, Grolier's, and Encarta. Expect to see a lot more encyclopedias available on CD. A newer one, Infopedia, is competing directly with the big three. Webster has a new one they are marketing as a supplement to one you may already have. Then there are encyclopedias that are geared just for children. Microsoft will be releasing Explorapedia in early 1995. Knowledge Adventure has two for kids, My First Encyclopedia for kids 3-7 and The Random House Kid's Encyclopedia for ages 7-12. These are much more colorful, with great graphics and sound. The Random House version has videos of kids acting as tour guides for your child. With all the graphics and videos, this encyclopedia comes on two CDs. Mary Pride tells me they'll all be reviewed in future issues of PHS-stay tuned!
<p>
<strong>Hot New Educational Software</strong>
<p>
Some of the newer titles that you should look for: Freddi Fish And The Case Of The Missing Kelp Seeds. This title, from Humongous Entertainment, creators of the popular Putt-Putt and Fatty Bear series, is like having your child watch a cartoon but your child gets to interact with the characters while learning problem solving skills and facts about the ocean. A new title from Digital Impact, Ozzie's World, teaches science and ecology through games and stories. It also features a coloring book to paint on screen or print out to color by hand. The Discovery Channel's newest release is called Animal Safari. You can learn about animals with some very catchy songs, stories, and an interactive coloring book. This also has the nice feature of being able to switch to one of four different languages. Some titles to consider for children ages 3-8 are from Step Ahead Software (the publishers of Golden Books). They feature programs for learning letters and numbers, moving up to math and spelling. Children are guided by cute animated characters.
<p>
 Brderbund's newest title, Math Workshop, is geared for ages 6-12. This was one of the nicest products we saw. Besides teaching addition, subtraction, multiplication and division, it also teaches fractions, shape and pattern recognition, spatial orientation, symmetry, and more. This features great graphics and sound. It also has a twelve-minute video on the CD to help parents increase their children's enjoyment of math. 
<p>
One final company you may want to consider is the small upstart company, Tadpole Productions, founded by homeschoolers. They have just released their first two titles featuring Rick Ribbit, an animated frog. Adventures In Early Learning is geared for young children, teaching shapes, letter and number recognition, and other early activities. The other title, Ark Noodles Math Challenge, is a Mario Brothers-type title teaching math for kids grades 1-5. This is well done with arcade action and background music. All math problems and numbers are spoken as you play to help you memorize math problems. 
<p>
<strong>CD-ROM or Bust</strong>
<p>
Another COMDEX discovery: if you do not have a CD-ROM drive, you will need to get one. Almost every new title was being distributed on CD. As software is using more graphics, sound, and video it is just not practical to distribute on 312" disks. Look for more titles to be shipping on multiple CDs. One of the new games unveiled at COMDEX ships on four CDs! 
<p>
Yes, at Comdex the future is definitely now. It's big, it's overwhelming, and it moves so fast you need to be a jack rabbit-or a PHS reader-to stay on top of it. New advances in technology make the computer a better teacher than ever-and provide a possible peephole into your home for government. Events like COMDEX help us keep monitoring the uses, and potential abuses, of computers in your home as we head towards the 21st century. 
<p>
<hr>
<strong>COPYRIGHT INFORMATION</strong>
<br>Copyright 1994 Home Life Inc. 
<br>Originally published in Practical Homeschooling No. 8.
<br>All rights reserved. This article or any part of it may not be published on any Internet or WWW site, or any BBS, or any other electronic or print medium, or any other medium, without our expression written permission. To request permission, please fax 314-225-0743 and describe the article, where you would like to publish it, and how many people you expect to read your publication. We will get back to you with our response as soon as possible.
</body>

