<CENTER><H1>Homeschool World Terms and Conditions</H1></CENTER>
Ad prices are locked in for the term of this contract. Otherwise,
prices and conditions are subject to change without notice.<P>
We reserve the right to refuse any ad at any time.<P>
We will fax or mail you a printout of your classified or Web page for you to approve. Upon
approval, the page(s) or classified(s) will be put up on our site. Your one year or six months
dates from the day your ad is released to our site.<P>
Ads are accepted on the representation that the advertiser and its agency have the legal right to use
any and all quotes, text, graphics, and other material used in their ad. In consideration
of such publication, the advertiser and the agency agree to assume all legal liability, losses, and
legal fees related to their ads placed on our WWW site. These include but are not limited to
claims and suits for plagiarism, libel, copyright infringement, trademark violations, or 
invasion of privacy. They indemnify and hold harmless this company and its owners and
workers from any such charges or suits.<P>
We will not be responsible for events beyond our control which cause our site to go down in
full or in part. We also will not be liable for any losses due to the site being inaccessible.<P>
If we make a typo in your ad, our liability is limited to fixing it.<P>
If paid for by credit card, by agreeing to our terms and conditions, you hereby authorize Home Life, Inc., to charge your credit card for the WWW page(s)
or link(s) you have signed up for when each term of service expires.<P>
You may cancel any ad or link any time and receive a pro-rated refund of the amount already paid, minus the nonrefundable set-up fees, fees for digitizing any optional video or audio samples, and any optional registration fees.<P>
Cancellations must be sent in writing on your letterhead, with an authorized signature. They can be sent by fax or mail.<P>
No conditions other than those set forth in this rate sheet shall be binding on us unless 
specifically agreed to in writing by Bill or Mary Pride.<P>
