<TITLE>A goddess - Athena</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" LINK="E02020" VLINK="C65050">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="Olympians.gif"><P><HR><P>
<H1><B>Athena<BR>(A-theen-uh)</H1></B><P>
Athena, the goddess of wisdom and war, is the highest goddess under Hera.
     There are several stories of how Athena came into being. According to the most 
popular story, Metis, the Titaness of wisdom, was due to have Zeus' baby. Zeus heard that any baby 
Metis had would be greater than its father, so he turned Metis into a fly and swallowed 
her. Later, Zeus developed a bad headache. He asked Hephaestos to split his head open, 
which he did, knowing that he could not harm an immortal. From Zeus' head appeared 
Athena, in full armor.<BR>
     Athena is sometimes known as Pallas. This is because of the time Athena 
accidentally killed a friend named Pallas while they were practicing with their spears. 
To show her grief, she called herself Pallas Athena.<BR>
     Athena was also the goddess of crafts. One day Princess Arachne boasted that she 
was a better weaver than even Athena. Athena then challenged her to a contest. As each 
wove her most beautiful work, Athena was angered to find that the princess' work was as 
good as her own. In her fury, she tore it up. Arachne was frightened and tried to hang 
herself. Athena was ashamed at what she had done and turned Arachne into a spider to 
save her from the impending death.<BR>
     Although she was the goddess of war, Athena preferred to settle disputes by 
reasoning. However, when she was involved in combat, she was unbeatable. She always wore 
armor, and was the keeper of Zeus' shield, the aegis, and his helmet. The owl is her 
bird, signifying her wisdom.<P><HR><P>To return to the main Mythology Project page, click <A HREF="http://www.home-school.com/myth/myth.html">here.</A><P><HR><P><H5><I>Research done by Emily Sawyer in November of 1996.</H5></I></CENTER>
</DOC>
