<TITLE>Other gods - Pan</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" LINK="E02020" VLINK="C65050">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="other.gif"><p>
<H1><B>Pan</H1></B><P>
<p>Pan was one of the most ancient of the Grecian deities.  He originated in the
mountainous area in the center of the Peloponnese.  This region was populated primarily
by herdsmen, and the principle livestock was goats. True to his geographical origin, Pan
became the herdsman's god and was seen as half goat.  Believed to be the son of
Hermes, he was recognized as a deity by all.  However, he was not considered immortal,
nor was he ever allowed on Mount Olympus.  

<p>His father, Hermes, was a great musician, and he gave that trait to Pan.  Pan
played an instrument which he fashioned out of reeds.  It looked like a small pipe organ,
but it was played like a flute.  Because Pan was credited as its inventor, it was known as a
pan pipe and became a favorite instrument of herdsmen.  Pan played his pipes with such
skill that his music could charm both gods and humans.

<p>The news of Pan's death was told by the winds to a sailor named Thamus.  While
standing watch during a storm, Thamus heard the winds say "Thamus, are you there? 
When you reach port, take care to proclaim that the great god Pan is dead."  Thamus did
as he was told, and Pan's death was mourned by many.  Some herdsman refused to
believe that their patron was dead, and maintained his alters long after he supposedly
passed from earth to Hades.

<p>Pan was a playful god who lived in the mountains with goats, not in the palaces of
Mount Olympus.  Because of this, the common people of the Hellenic world more readily
identified with Pan than any of the Olympian gods.
<P><HR><P>
<A HREF="myth.html">Click here to return to the main Mythology Project page.</A><P><HR><P>
<H5><I>Research done in January of 1997 by Micah Valine.</H5></I>
