<TITLE>JCL online</TITLE>
<BODY background="background.gif" TEXT=000000>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="jcl.GIF" ALT="JCCL logo."><BR>
<IMG SRC="motto.gif" ALT="Mottos Page."><P>
 <B>  Junior Classical League gives tests on mottos -- potentially
ribbons and maybe trophies at stake here.  Don't just read these and dump
them.  Keep a notebook, learn them, and be ready for a motto category for
future quiz bowls.</B><P>
<HR>
<H3> For certain state mottos, click <A HREF="statem.HTML">here!</A><BR>
 For miscellaneous mottos and sayings, look below.</H3>
 <HR>
<B>Per Veritatem Vis:</B>  "Strength Through Truth".<BR>
Motto of the University of Washington<P>

<B>Discere Si Cupias Intra: Salvere Iubemus:</B> "If you wish to learn, enter: 
we welcome you"<BR>
An inscription at Brookings Hall at the University of Washington<P>

<B>Cedunt Horae, Opera Manent:</B> "The hours go by, the works remain"<BR>
An inscription at Brookings Hall at the University of Washington<P>

The motto for Southern Methodist University is  <B>"Veritas Liberabit Vos,"</B> the
truth will make you free.<P>

<B>Semper Fidelis</B> "Always Faithful"<BR>
U.S. Marine Corps.<P>

<B>Semper Vigilans</B> "Always Vigilant"<BR> Civil Air Patrol<P>

The motto of the Reformation:  <B>sola fide, sola scriptura, sola Christo, 
sola Deo gloria, sola  gratia.</B>  "by faith alone, by Scripture alone, by 
Christ alone, for the glory of God alone, by grace alone"<P>

Motto: <B>"Citius, Altius, Fortius."</B> Latin meaning "faster, higher, braver," or 
the modern interpretation "swifter, higher, stronger." The motto was coined by Father 
Didon, a French educator, in 1895.<P>

Constantines Motto: Constantine adopted these words <B>"In Hoc signo vinces"</B> - 
"By this sign thou shalt conquer." as his motto after having seen a vision in the sky 
of a luminous cross bearing these words on the night before the Battle of Milvian Bridge in 312.  He took this quite literally, and put the cross on his own shield as well as that of his men.  Historians have called his victory at Milvian Bridge the great turning point, the end of antiquity and the beginning of Christendom.<P>

<B>"Christus Dominus resurrexi"</B> Christ, the Lord is risen!<P>

<B>Gloria in excelsis Deo:</B> Glory to God in the highest<P>

<B>Deus dirigit:</B>  God directs<P>
	
<B>Deo volente:</B> God willing<P>

<B>Iesus Nazarenus, Rex Iudaecorum:</B> Jesus the Nazarene, king of the Jews<P>

<B>magna cum  laude:</B> with high praise<P>

<B>summa cum laude:</B>	with highest praises<P>

<B>Terra incognita:</B> unknown land<P>

<B>e pluribus unum:</B> from many, one<P>
<HR>

Back to the <A HREF="http://www.monmouth.com/user_pages/sporter/jcl.html">Junior Classical Cyber League</A> home page. <BR>
