<TITLE>My Favorite Mac Games</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#000000 TEXT=#00FF00 LINK=FFFF00 VLINK=FF0000>
<CENTER><H1>The Best Shareware Mac Games</H1></CENTER>
So you've seen it all. You've stared down the jaws of Doom, machinegunned space aliens,
nuked Tie Fighters, jumped on the heads of weird little walking mushrooms, and kicked
and punched your way to computer game boredom.<P>
Wanna do it all over again? Try these!<P>
<B><A HREF="http://www.bungie.com/downloads/ftp.html">Marathon 3D</A></B><BR>
You are a member of the security personnel on the colony ship Marathon. But the vicious
aliens are attacking your ship and trying to take it over. They may try to head to Earth,
so you have to warn Earth then blow those alien stinkers to kingdom come. The teleport
computer (which is being hacked by the aliens) plans your strategic attacks and warps
you to the necessary destinations. You may be abducted by Durandal, the rogue teleport
computer, on the way, but that's part of the bargain, right? So ultimately you save the
human race. (ho-hum) The only other possible ending would be getting blown to shreds
by aliens.<BR>
But that's not all! There are two other Marathon games! Marathon II has better graphics
and still runs pretty smoothly. In Marathon II the WHOLE GAME is spent performing missions
for the rogue computer.<BR>
Marathon: Infinity completes the trilogy. Personally, I have no idea what Infinity is
all about; the graphics are too jerky on my lowly little PowerMac and I got disgusted.<BR>
These games feature LOTS of weapons, lava you can drown in, what a way to go, and water you
can swim in! (and not only that, it's realistic enough not to let you use your weapons
underwater!)<BR>
And Marathon has great multiplayer options. Unfortunately, unless you register and get
the complete game, you'll never get to have more than two players. Registered version
comes with four registration codes so you can have four players in a game.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.escape-velocity.com/files/releases.html"><B>Escape Velocity</B></A><BR>
A 2D spaceship game. But this one is more than just a shoot-'em-up. You don't fly
around shooting hordes of weak puny little aliens for cash to buy more weapons, you have
laws to abide by. About as realistic as a science-fiction game is going to get.<BR>
There are two main factions in the universe at the time you start the game: the Rebels
and the Confederation. (Feds for short.) The Feds had teamed up to fight the alien menace
50 years before, but when the aliens were destroyed the Feds didn't want to give up their
power. They overtaxed their worlds, built themselves armies, and basically built their
pompous selves up. The Rebels did not like this so they constructed an alliance nearly
as powerful to fight the Feds.<BR>
Rebels and Feds are not the only ships you will see. And they won't attack you without
reason until you start working for one side or the other. Also you will see traders, private
vessels, shipping companies, and Pirates. Everybody hates the Pirates. The Pirates hate
everybody. If they see you in the same system as them, the Pirates will try to attack your
ship and steal your stuff. The downside is the Pirates give no quarter. The GOOD thing
about Pirates is that NOBODY will care if you kill them. You can make quite a respectable
business, pirating from Pirates. But the best and safest way to make money is to simply
carry goods from one planet to another for hire.<BR>
And, should you grow tired of the game, you can download plugins to completely change
the universe and begin your exploration anew!<BR>
One of the most detailed games I have ever seen, Escape Velocity can be tried out for 30
days, FULL VERSION! However, after those 30 days, an invulnerable ship will start attacking
you whenever you enter any system. Bummer. Still, you but have to pay 20 or 30 $$$$ to
the company that makes the game to make the invulnerable ships stop, and by the end of
the 30 days you'll be so attached to the game you can't bear NOT to register it.<P>

<B>Simple Addictive Arcade Games for the Testosterone Gifted</B><P>
<A HREF="http://www.ambrosiasw.com/Ambrosia_Products/Swoop.html"><B>Swoop</B></A><BR>
One of those games in which you dodge left and right at the bottom of the screen shooting
at enemies on the top of the screen which are continuously bombing you or trying to kill
you with a kamikaze dive. There are countless games like this. However, this one looks
and sounds the nicest. Costs $15 to register, and though you'll get an annoying 20-second
delay every time you start the game until you register at least it isn't a truncaded edition.<P>

<A HREF="http://www.ambrosiasw.com/Ambrosia_Products/Maelstrom.html"><B>Maelstrom</B></A><BR>
A simple shoot-em-up-and-try-to-top-the-high-score game. You are a small ship which must
fly through the Maelstrom asteroid belt, destroying all the asteroids and enemy fighters
in order to make it safe for shipping.<BR>
This game is made in the "asteroids" style. You rotate the ship, shoot, thrust, and activate
shields in order to tame the asteroid field. It's decidedly 2D, though the graphics look
3D rendered. And the sounds are a glory to behold.<P>

<A HREF="ftp://mirror.aol.com/pub/info-mac/game/arc/solarian-ii-104.hqx"><B>Solarian II</B></A><BR>
Another Space Invaders-esque game, in which your real purpose is to beat the high scores
by nuking aliens. Of course, the aliens are nuking you right back, so that makes it tough.
Again, this is one of the best of its class because of its superior graphics, sounds, 
and the fact that it will run on practically ANY 256-color Mac.<P>

If this hasn't turned you into a permanent computer game junkie, I'm sorry. If you know
of a game that SHOULD be here and isn't, e-mail me at <A HREF="MAILTO:Joseph@Home-School.COM">
Joseph@home-school.com</A>.<P>

<A HREF="JoesPage.HTML">Back to Joseph Pride's Homepage</A>|<A HREF=HTTP://www.home-school.com>Homeschool World, my dad's Web site</A>|<A HREF="HTTP://www.home-school.com/HSMall.HTML">Homeschool Mall, my job on my dad's Web site</A>
</DOC>
