<TITLE>Harkin International - Declassified Info</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#000000 TEXT=#00FF00>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="Harkin.GIF"><BR>
<H1>Declassified 17/62/8395</H1></CENTER>
George P. Harkin was enlisted in the IGOSS for 3 years under the alias of Clarence 
Portly then retired, carefully covering his trail.<P>
Fortunately, his personal safety will no longer be at risk should this info be 
declassified.<P>
Using the large amount of money he gained as an agent performing dangerous misisons, 
Harkin began a research and development company which discovered Densaplast.<P>
Densaplast was discovered on an asteroid which reached Earth approximately 3 hours 
before the supernova of Alkaid was visible on telescopes. The asteroid was 
approximately 3 inches in width, but due to the speed of its travel it created a crater
about half a mile wide. The asteroid was discovered by infrared sensors.<P>
Harkin purchased the asteroid for an outlandish price, then using his top-secret transformation
equipment he synthesized it. The element occurred in 3 isotopes. One was a semiconductor,
one conducted electricity as well as pure copper, and one didn't conduct electricity at
all. With these three kinds of densaplast, complex machines could be made.<P>
Densaplast, even as a .05 millimeter thick foil, was virtually impossible to bend, and the foil snapped back
into its original shape after being barely bent by a 2,000,000 volt compressor. The only
way that densaplast could be molded was by heating it up in a blast furnace. And even
then, the only thing that could make it stay bent was a magnet. When bent by a magnet, 
the densaplast would maintain its new shape.<P>
Therefore, parts for machines could be constructed by being magnetically pulled into
ceramic molds. And the process was very expensive.<P>
Harkin kept all plans in a densaplast safe so there was no way they could be stolen.<P>
All this research took millions of dollars to perform, but then Harkin received grants 
from America, Russia, and Germany to create an airtight indestructible space station.
The project took 15 years and it made Harkin International a fortune.<P>
Harkin died in an industrial accident at his company, at the age of 45. The company passed
on to his son. The younger Harkin slowly disbanded the company after creating one last
secret project for his own private use. The only project the company had created for
personal use was one suit of combat armor. Using densaplast machinery, the armor had
sensors and motors to amplify human strength, heating circuits and cooling circuits that
could be activated by a control pad on the chest, and superspeed arms. <BR>
<A HREF="Fists.GIF"><IMG SRC="FistsSmall.GIF"></A><BR>
Using inertial damper technology, the Fists of Fury could accelerate to MACH 3 in .012 seconds
without reducing the operator inside to pulp.<P>
After several tests<BR>
<A HREF="Test.JPG"><IMG SRC="Test.GIF"></A><BR>
Harkin finished disbanding the company after one last secret development and began a short career
with the army, performing impossible missions with his indestructible armor keeping out projectiles
and the inertial dampers keeping explosive concussions from hurting him. He then vanished, literally.<P>
He formally resigned from the army, then while standing right in front of several security
cameras he vanished. Who knows where he's gone... Some suggest he was responsible for many
alien sightings in the 20th century, some suggest he somehow teleported to a tropical island
and spent the rest of his life on a hammock under a palm tree. Some even suggest he was
abducted by aliens.<P>
Possibly one of the greatest mysteries of the 82nd century: Harkin was making a profit,
his business was growing, he was creating great cities on the bottom of the sea and in outer
space, and he had control of the most indestructible material known to man. Why would he
simply vanish? How was it done? Perhaps it has something to do with the strange anomalies on sensors near his factory. Who can tell?<P>
<A HREF="JoesPage.HTML">Back to Joseph Pride's Homepage</A>|<A HREF=HTTP://www.home-school.com>Homeschool World, my dad's Web site</A>|<A HREF="HTTP://www.home-school.com/HSMall.HTML">Homeschool Mall, my job on my dad's Web site</A><P>

This material is entirely fictitious. Any resemblance to cheap paperbacks, alive or dead,
is completely unintentional.
</DOC>
